## Methodology that worked — the four layers

Ads and integrity defences in modern Play Store apps are layered. Patching one layer leaks crashes from the next. Work outside-in:

- **Layer 0 — Defeat anti-tamper (Pairip).** Nothing else matters if the app self-kills on signature mismatch. Stub `SignatureCheck.verifyIntegrity` (and equivalents) to `return-void`, remove the `LicenseActivity` / `LicenseContentProvider` from the manifest. Do this first because every later change re-signs the APK, which trips the check.
- **Layer 1 — Manifest scrub.** Auto-init providers, activities, services, receivers, and meta-data are how SDKs bootstrap before any app code runs. Strip them by `android:name` prefix match against a known-bad list. This alone removes the majority of ad surface and most network calls.
- **Layer 2 — Stub SDK init entry points.** `MobileAds.initialize`, `AudienceNetworkAds.initialize`, `PAGSdk.init`, AppLovin SDK init, etc. The app's own code calls these from `Application.onCreate` or first activity. Replace bodies with no-ops.
- **Layer 3 — Leave the SDK dex bytecode in place.** Do **not** delete the ad SDK classes. The app references them via reflection, `Class.forName`, and direct class literals scattered through obfuscated code; removing them yields `ClassNotFoundException` from places you can't easily find. Dead classes are cheap; missing classes are fatal.

Order matters because each layer's failure modes mask the next layer's bugs.

## Architecture matters — the v7a vs arm64 lesson

Modern flagships (Dimensity 9000+, Snapdragon 8 Gen series) are 64-bit-only with no AArch32 userspace. A `armeabi-v7a`-only split installs with `INSTALL_FAILED_NO_MATCHING_ABIS`.

Lesson: **always `unzip -l <split>.apk | grep "lib/"` before committing to a build.** Mirror sites (APKPure et al.) sometimes hand out v7a-flavoured xapks based on browser fingerprint. The file looks complete; the device disagrees.

## Pairip integration tiers

Pairip ships in two distinct flavours. Identifying which one you're up against decides whether the project is feasible at all.

- **License-only Pairip.** Manifest has `LicenseActivity` and `LicenseContentProvider`; smali has a `SignatureCheck` class with a `verifyIntegrity` method. Defeat: stub `verifyIntegrity` to `return-void`, delete the manifest entries. Done.
- **VMP-protected Pairip.** Real method bodies are replaced at build time with calls to `com.pairip.VMRunner.invoke(...)`. The original bytecode is encrypted and lives inside `libpairipcore.so`. Without the matching native lib every VMP'd method becomes a hole that returns `null` / `0`. Cascading NPEs surface in unrelated code: protobuf parsers crash, `Service.onCreate` crashes, `AlarmService` crashes.

**VMP cannot be defeated by smali patching.** Either obtain a build that ships the matching `libpairipcore.so` (the user's installed APK does, by definition), or pick a different upstream that doesn't ship VMP.

## The pivot that worked

When upstream mirrors fail (wrong ABI, VMP without lib), `adb pull` the user's already-installed APK off the device:

```
adb shell pm path <package.name>
adb pull /data/app/.../base.apk
```

Why this works:

- ABI is guaranteed correct — Play Store delivered exactly what this device runs.
- Native libs are present and matched, including `libpairipcore.so` if VMP is used.
- The Play Store sometimes ships a lighter Pairip integration (license-only) than what mirrors carry, depending on the rollout track.

Use the device as your source of truth whenever the user already has the app installed.

## Single-APK vs splits tradeoff

Play Store delivery is `base.apk + config.<abi>.apk + config.<density>.apk`. `adb install-multiple` requires all three signed with the same key. Apktool **cannot cleanly rebuild config splits** — they have no `<application>` tag, the manifest is structurally minimal, and reassembly produces APKs the installer rejects.

Workaround: collapse to a single fat APK.

1. Extract `lib/<abi>/*.so` from the ABI split.
2. Place them into `decoded/lib/<abi>/` of the apktool'd base.
3. Remove `requiredSplitTypes` and `isSplitRequired` attributes from the `<manifest>` tag.
4. Set `android:extractNativeLibs="true"` on `<application>`.
5. `apktool b`, sign, install single APK.

Density splits are usually safe to drop entirely.

## Coexistence via package rename

To install the modded build alongside the original, rename the package consistently. Sites to update — miss any one and you get silent provider crashes:

- `<manifest package="...">` in AndroidManifest.xml
- Every `android:authorities="..."` (FileProvider, WorkManager, ad SDKs leaving residue)
- Every `<permission android:name="...">` and `<uses-permission>` referencing the app's own permissions
- **Every smali file containing the old package as a literal string.** `grep -rl '"<old.package>"' smali*/` typically returns 8–15 hits — launchers and similar apps construct ContentProvider URIs and intent actions from hardcoded strings; obfuscators skip them.

## App display label

`android:label="@string/app_name"` almost always resolves to a `<string name="app_name">` in `res/values/strings.xml`. Update only the default locale file — Android falls back to it when a localised variant is missing.

## Toolchain setup on macOS (no sudo path)

```
brew install apktool android-platform-tools openjdk@21 android-commandlinetools
export JAVA_HOME=/opt/homebrew/opt/openjdk@21
sdkmanager "build-tools;34.0.0" "platform-tools"
```

- **Avoid `brew install --cask temurin`** — requires sudo for the pkg installer and fails non-interactively. The keg-only `openjdk@21` formula needs no sudo and works fine for apktool, apksigner, and zipalign.
- Build tools live at `/opt/homebrew/share/android-commandlinetools/build-tools/<v>/`. Binaries: `zipalign`, `apksigner`, `aapt`, `aapt2`.

## The debug loop is logcat, not Android Studio

Modded smali has no source map. The IDE debugger is useless. The actual loop is tight and text-based:

```
adb shell monkey -p <package> -c android.intent.category.HOME 1
adb logcat -d -b crash -t 200 | grep -A30 "FATAL EXCEPTION"
```

Each crash points at one specific class/method. Patch it, rebuild, reinstall, repeat. Convergence is typically 1–3 iterations per build.

## Common patterns and their fixes

- **`UnsatisfiedLinkError: dlopen failed: library "X" not found`** — a class is calling `System.loadLibrary("X")` in its `<clinit>` for a native lib you removed. Stub the `<clinit>` to drop the `loadLibrary` call. Replace the class's `native` methods with no-op Java bodies returning safe defaults.
- **`RuntimeException: Unable to instantiate provider <FQCN>`** — manifest still references a `<provider>` whose backing class you removed. Remove the provider entry too. Same applies to `<service>` and `<receiver>`.
- **`NullPointerException` from a method that should have returned a real value** — VMP'd method without the native lib backing it. There's no smali fix; pivot.
- **`INSTALL_FAILED_UPDATE_INCOMPATIBLE`** — signing certificate mismatch versus the installed copy. `adb uninstall <pkg>` first, or rename the package to coexist.

## Smali stubbing recipe

To make a method a no-op while preserving its signature, annotations, and parameter directives:

- Keep the `.method` line, all `.annotation` blocks, and `.param` directives untouched.
- Replace the body with a minimal return.
- Set `.locals` to the smallest count needed for the return value.

| Return type | Body |
|-------------|------|
| `V` (void) | `.locals 0` then `return-void` |
| `L...;` (object) | `.locals 1` / `const/4 v0, 0x0` / `return-object v0` |
| `I` `Z` `B` `S` `C` | `.locals 1` / `const/4 v0, 0x0` / `return v0` |
| `J` (long) | `.locals 2` / `const-wide/16 v0, 0x0` / `return-wide v0` |
| `D` (double) | `.locals 2` / `const-wide/16 v0, 0x0` / `return-wide v0` |
| `F` (float) | `.locals 1` / `const/4 v0, 0x0` / `return v0` |

Don't touch other methods. Don't strip annotations — some are read by reflection.

